Hey! I noticed that when doing a lot of note operations over a longer period of time, the browser heap memory grows and grows. After digging through heap snapshots, I found the note cache littered with objects. Because [strudel](https://strudel.tidalcycles.org/) makes heavy use of this lib, the heap happens to creep to over 100MB in a matter of minutes, compared to ~10MB without using tonal functions.

Example of a problematic call stack:

`Note.transpose("A", "3m")` -> `coordToNote([0])` -> `note({step: 0, alt: 0, dir: undefined })`

The cache inside the `note` function works like this:

```js
const cache = new Map();

/* .. */
function note(src) {
    const cached = cache.get(src);
    if (cached) {
        return cached;
    }
    const value = /* .. */
    cache.set(src, value);
    return value;
}
```

Now the problem is that `cache.get({ /* .. */ })` will always be undefined. Try running this in the browser console:

```js
const cache = new Map();
cache.set({ foo: true }, 'hello');
cache.get({ foo: true}); // undefined
```

The memory leak happens with `cache.set(src, value);`, making sure the object stays in memory until forever.

An easy fix would be to skip the cache logic when `src` is an object.

